The paper deals with the sample complexity of differentially private algorithms, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of theoretical computer science. Specifically, the paper uses techniques from coding theory (fingerprinting codes) to derive lower bounds on the sample complexity of such algorithms. This suggests that the paper is likely to be classified under cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.IT (information theory), or cs.CR (cryptography and security). Additionally, the paper deals with the accuracy of counting queries on databases, which is a problem that is often studied in the context of machine learning and data mining. This suggests that the paper may also be classified under cs.LG (machine learning) or cs.CC (computational complexity).
